<TEXT>
a tropical storm watch for the hawaiian islands 
was discontinued but high surf advisories were in effect as 
hurricane uleki moved away from the state the national weather 
service said 
at 2 pm sunday or 8 pm edt the hurricane was 385 miles 
southwest of honolulu and 350 miles southwest of lihue kauai 
moving to the west at 12 mph with maximum sustained winds of 80 mph 
and gusts to 100 mph meteorologist clarence lee said 
ulekis westward movement lessened the threat of damaging winds 
for oahu where honolulu is located kauai and niihau lee said 
however a high surf advisory remained in effect for all 
southern coasts that were pounded by large waves from the storm 
rescuers assisted 19 people saturday in 5 to 6foot waves off 
waikiki beach and nearby ala moana beach according to lifeguard 
capt jim howe 
a body was discovered sunday off maunalua bay eight miles east 
of honolulu but it was not immediately known if the death was 
related to the storm police said 
uleki was expected to continue moving westward and gradually 
weaken to the point where it could be downgraded from hurricane 
status this afternoon lee said 
when the storm took an unexpected turn toward the islands 
friday winds near the center gusted to 150 mph 
uleki is hawaiian for ulysses the weather service in hawaii 
said the central pacific region has its own list of hawaiian names 
for storms in the region next will be wila followed by aka ekeka 
and hale 
so few storms originate in the region that the list is used over 
and over and does not start the year with a name beginning with 
the letter a as in the atlantic or other regions of the pacific 
