<TEXT>
us aid has helped prevent the takeover of el 
salvador by leftist guerrillas but has failed to solve the 
underlying social problems that sparked the insurgency say four 
us army lieutenant colonels who have served in the central 
american nation and in vietnam 
the american foundation for conducting small wars is 
defective said the report prepared while the four officers were 
on fellowships at the john f kennedy school of government at 
harvard university in cambridge mass 
the unsatisfactory results of the us effort in el salvador 
which the authors described as neither victory nor defeat stem in 
part from local conditions and in part from the failure of the 
reagan administration to clearly define its goals they said 
the united states provided resources not on the basis of some 
overall vision of success but in response to successive and 
increasingly acute crises said the four us officers lt cols 
aj bacevich james d hallums richard h white and thomas f 
young 
administration officials failed to formulate a longterm 
strategy to help cure the social and economic ills of el salvador 
and did not coordinate the efforts of us military and civilian 
advisers said the report 
the report also concluded that the us military despite the 
lessons of vietnam helped mold the salvadoran armed forces into a 
organization better suited for big europeanstyle conflicts than 
third world guerrilla wars 
their findings were contained in a 58page booklet published by 
the institute for foreign policy analysis affiliated with the 
fletcher school on law and diplomacy at tufts university in 
medford mass 
as long as the united states remains a great power american 
involvement in small wars will recur with some frequency they 
wrote to find fault with american military policy in a 
particular instance is not to suggest that the united states is 
incapable of effective assistance to an ally threatened by an 
insurgency the important thing is to get it right they wrote 
offering the following suggestions 
make room for the study of small wars in military schools 
clarify organizational responsibilities for fighting small 
wars in washington and in the field 
before undertaking any intervention establish a vision of 
what you hope to accomplish and a consensus of political support to 
sustain that vision 
send your first team and permit its members the latitude to 
get the job done rather than training all capable officers to 
fight only largescale wars 
avoid introducing inappropriate technology 
the lieutenant colonels questioned other us officers with 
experience in el salvador and found that none of them viewed the 
salvadoran insurgency as primarily a military problem 
none believed that killing guerrillas alone would win the war 
all expressed the belief that only through political social and 
economic reform could the salvadoran government hope to defeat the 
insurgency the report said 
the us effort was also hampered by unreliable baloneyslice 
funding doled out by an unenthusiastic congress the report said 
in addition the salvadoran armed forces have been molded along 
the lines of the us military which is better suited to major 
ground offensives than to smallunit guerrilla fighting 
almost instinctively americans take a rich mans approach to 
war the report said they view us access to technology 
however expensive as offering a significant comparative advantage 
over potential adversaries it said 
us military advisers have imbued salvadoran officers with the 
same outlook the report said take the example of artillery the 
salvadoran army fields 54 105 mm howitzers employing them in one 
or two gun sections used primarily for harassing and interdiction 
american experience in vietnam demonstrated that harassing and 
interdiction fires in an insurgency are at best wasteful and at 
worst counterproductive nonetheless the report said us 
advisers endorsed the request of the salvadoran military to 
replace its current howitzers with a new model that is identical in 
caliber but airtransportable 
similarly the us military backed a salvadoran request for 
more sophisticated fighters and helicopters although scarcely a 
week goes by without an aircraft being destroyed or damaged in an 
incident stemming from questionable maintenance or dubious flying 
skills by salvadorans inadequately trained to handle 
supersophisticated gadgetry 
moreover guerrilla forces in el salvador are no longer capable 
of fighting major engagements in which sophisticated fighters and 
helicopters can help and now operate in smaller units and 
emphasize hitandrun attacks in which such air support is of 
limited use the authors wrote 
</TEXT>
