<TEXT>
two visions of vermont have 
collided in this picturesque hilltop village of austere white 
buildings and a village green 
one has to do with polished antiques fine food and weekends of 
leisure in the countryside the other has to do with morning 
chores rutted pastures and muddy shoes 
the dispute is being aired in hearing rooms and involves an 
effort by a small college here to build a genuine livestock barn 
within sight of the manicured english gardens of the inn on the 
common with its croquet lawn clay tennis court and adirondack 
chairs from which guests take in the panoramic view 
people come here for peace and quiet they dont come here to 
be put in the middle of a farm yard said michael schmitt who 
with his wife penny opened the inn 14 years ago after leaving 
their jobs in new york in investment banking and advertising 
students at sterling college a 75student school offering 
programs in farming and forestry served up with a backtotheland 
ethic are erecting a barn whose rafters can be seen from the inns 
garden 
the schmitts opposition to the barn and a second one planned 
nearby was dismissed recently by the district 7 environmental 
commission based in st johnsbury but they have appealed to the 
state environmental board 
mrs schmitt said the barn violates the artistic intent of the 
inn whose gardens were built in the 1930s and are part of a 
historic district on the national register of historic places 
the idea is to create not just pretty flower clumps but to 
create a total outdoor room if you will she said 
we are not antifarming she said this is not a farm 
versus tourism issue tourism and farming are bound together in 
vermont people come to vermont to look at the beautiful farms and 
fields 
a vermont view can contain barns she said but you do what is 
appropriate where you find it 
construction permits are granted in vermont under a 1970 
development control law written to preserve the states rural 
character a district 7 commission member said this is the first 
time in his memory that the law has been used to oppose 
construction of barns 
sterling college president robert cowen said the school needs 
the barns to continue its agricultural programs 
we have tried to do this with the least negative impact as 
possible on our neighbors he said 
in its ruling the district commission dismissed the schmitts 
concerns about barnyard noises smells and insects wafting over a 
fence and onto their property the barn is about 800 feet from the 
inn 
although animals may occasionally be heard at the inn and at 
area residences this noise will be similar to the sounds produced 
by other farming operations in the area the commission wrote 
legally construction can go on during the schmitts appeal to 
the state environmental board but the college is proceeding at its 
own risk 
on the issue of aesthetics the commission applied a test in 
vermont law that bars projects having an undue adverse impact 
it found that while the impact of the barns would be adverse it 
would not be undue 
